SQL Rules in Calculated Insights

When using SQL in calculated insights in Data Cloud, keep these rules and guidelines in mind to create successful functions.

REQUIRED EDITIONS
Available in: Lightning Experience

These rules apply to the top-level query in Calculated Insights.

A measure is identified by aggregation functions. A query must contain at least one measure.
An attribute that isn’t used in a SELECT clause’s aggregation function is treated as a dimension and appears in a GROUP-BY clause.
The WHERE clause can’t have an aggregate expression.
The WHERE clause can’t have a dimension or measure alias.
The GROUP-BY clause is an expression (non-aggregate) involving non-aliases.
The GROUP-BY clause refers to a dimension alias, but the alias can’t be part of an expression.
The GROUP-BY clause can’t include a measure alias or an aggregate function.
You can’t include an ORDER-BY clause in a top-level SELECT statement.
The PARTITION-BY and ORDER-BY clauses in a RANK function can be expressions, aggregate or otherwise.
A RANK clause involving an aggregate expression is treated as a measure.
A measure resulting from a RANK clause is non-aggregatable.
A CASE expression involving an aggregation function is treated as a measure.
A measure resulting from CASE(WHEN <aggregation function>) is non-aggregatable.
You can’t aggregate within an aggregation.
You can’t include a distinct operator in the top-level query.
The dimension name for a SELECT clause can’t be the same as the original name. For example, an error occurs if you use "as customer_id__c" for this query: SELECT UnifiedIndividual__dlm.Id__c as customer_id__c.
You can use multiline comments ( /* */).
